I'm so happy to announce my first giveaway on my 19th birthday and to celebrate 150k! I'm really grateful for your support and love and that's why I decided to do a DRAWING for 2 of you!✨ It's an internation giveaway with shipping included, so it would be totally free! 🎉

テーマは「普通」

普通さぁ！
の普通って何基準なんだろう。
あなたは普通と思っていてもこちらは普通じゃないかもしれない。
基準なんて人それぞれであって押し付けるのは違うと思います。
悪いことしなければ普通である必要もないです。
人それぞれだから。

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." 🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." 🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." 🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

🌺IMPORTANT INFO🌺

Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." Just need to let everyone know that due to unforeseen circumstances I have had to pull out of Open Studios this year. My apologies to anyone who’d planned to visit my studio in particular. All other Maroondah artists will still be opening their doors and there is a fabulous selection of studios to choose from.
For those of you wanting to purchase art please send me a direct message. I will also be having a little solo exhibition in November and my eucalyptus leaves will be exhibited as part of ReFraming Nature at the Royal Botanical Gardens Melbourne in a couple of weeks. ‘Out Of Slumber’ in Queenscliff (@queenscliffgalleryworkshop) finishes on September 15th, so you have just one more week to see all the beautiful pieces exhibited.
Wishing you a gorgeous weekend wherever you are 💗

@natgeo photo by @stevewinterphoto
"Here is Scarface with another spectacular failure going after a caiman. Scarface spent 4 days swimming and walking the aisles of his supermarket - the Pantanal rivers! - looking for a caiman dinner! Nature does not let you pick things off the shelves - you need to work very hard for your food! Nature is perfection. It gives us the air we breathe and the water we all need for our life.

Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970’s to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species." To see more amazing photos by @beverlyjoubert to purchase for your home, please visit one of our National Geographic Fine Art galleries. For locations, http://po.st/NGFA

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. “I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

JOHN SELL COTMAN In art, timing is everything, and Cotman got his wrong. Cursed with a classical eye in a romantic era, he was both behind the times and ahead of them. In his day he looked old-fashioned; now he looks modern. In fact his art is timeless because, being “bottomed in truth”, it was built to last. - Laura Gascoigne, The Spectator 21 May 2005 || Born 1782 in Norwich he made the fatal error of putting family before his art. His death in 1842 didn’t even rate an obituary in his native town.

“I like very much the qualities of lead - the surface, the heaviness. Some of the paintings were completely painted, and you only experience the lead at the edges; this gives the painting a very heavy feeling - it gives the colour a different density and weight. In other works the materials would be explicitly visible as grounds. I like to react on things, with the normal canvas you often have to kill the ground, give it something to react against. With the metals you already have something - its scratches, scrapes..” - Günther Förg #güntherförg#painter#painting#artist#sculptor#artprofessor#minimalism#formalism#maler#malerei#zeichner#printmaker#stedelijkmuseum#modernart#photographer#fineart#künstler#fragilebeauty#kunst#art#maxhetzler

I’m still on vacation in Crete trying to catch as many sun rays as possible before returning to Germany! I know I didn’t post much here on Instagram lately. I just don’t have the time. I’m working on a second children’s book, which will be released this fall (both of the books I illustrated will actually be released this fall) and I’m also working on the second book during my stay on Crete. Trying to make my office away from home as comfortable as possible. Working with such a beautiful view isn’t bad, right?

Anybody else who loves painting at the beach/ close to the sea as much as I do??? I’m using my iPad Pro, the @apple pencil and @procreate app to paint wherever I travel!
